        <!-- Columna Izquierda -->
        <div>
          <h2 class="text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
            Mortgage interest rate FAQs
          </h2>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
            Don't see your question here? We love helping people understand how rates work and what yours could be. Just talk to us.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Columna Derecha -->
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <!-- FAQ Item 1 -->
          <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 focus:outline-none focus:bg-gray-50">
              <span class="font-medium text-gray-900">What's a mortgage rate?</span>
              <svg class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
              A mortgage rate is the interest rate charged on a mortgage loan. It's the cost you pay each year to borrow money to buy your home, expressed as a percentage of the loan amount.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Item 2 -->
          <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 focus:outline-none focus:bg-gray-50">
              <span class="font-medium text-gray-900">How do mortgage rates work?</span>
              <svg class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
              Mortgage rates determine how much interest you'll pay on your home loan. A lower rate means lower monthly payments and less interest paid over the life of the loan. Rates can be fixed (staying the same) or adjustable (changing over time).
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Item 3 -->
          <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 focus:outline-none focus:bg-gray-50">
              <span class="font-medium text-gray-900">What factors determine mortgage rates?</span>
              <svg class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
              Several factors affect mortgage rates including your credit score, down payment amount, loan term, debt-to-income ratio, employment history, and current economic conditions like inflation and Federal Reserve policies.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Item 4 -->
          <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 focus:outline-none focus:bg-gray-50">
              <span class="font-medium text-gray-900">How do I get the best mortgage rate?</span>
              <svg class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
              To get the best rate, improve your credit score, save for a larger down payment, shop around with multiple lenders, consider shorter loan terms, and get pre-approved to show you're a serious buyer.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Item 5 -->
          <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 focus:outline-none focus:bg-gray-50">
              <span class="font-medium text-gray-900">What's a mortgage rate lock, and should I do it?</span>
              <svg class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
              A rate lock guarantees your interest rate for a specific period (usually 30-60 days) while you complete your home purchase. It protects you from rate increases but you won't benefit if rates drop. It's generally recommended in rising rate environments.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Item 6 -->
          <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 focus:outline-none focus:bg-gray-50">
              <span class="font-medium text-gray-900">What's the difference between interest rate and APR?</span>
              <svg class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
              The interest rate is the cost of borrowing money, while APR (Annual Percentage Rate) includes the interest rate plus other loan costs like origination fees, discount points, and mortgage insurance, giving you the true cost of the loan.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Item 7 -->
          <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 focus:outline-none focus:bg-gray-50">
              <span class="font-medium text-gray-900">What are mortgage points?</span>
              <svg class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
              Mortgage points are fees paid upfront to reduce your interest rate. One point typically costs 1% of your loan amount and reduces your rate by about 0.25%. Points make sense if you plan to stay in the home long enough to recoup the upfront cost.
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Item 8 -->
          <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
            <button class="faq-button w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-gray-50 focus:outline-none focus:bg-gray-50">
              <span class="font-medium text-gray-900">How often do mortgage rates change?</span>
              <svg class="faq-icon w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
              Mortgage rates can change daily or even multiple times per day based on economic factors, bond market movements, and lender policies. Rates are most volatile during economic uncertainty or major policy announcements.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
